value.value: A malignant neoplasm involving the glans penis.
Cancer or tumors of the ureter which may cause obstruction leading to hydroureter, hydronephrosis, and pyelonephritis. hematuria is a common symptom.
A benign smooth muscle neoplasm arising from the ureter. It is characterized by the presence of spindle cells with cigar-shaped nuclei, interlacing fascicles, and a whorled pattern.
A benign nerve sheath tumor composed of Schwann cells, occurring in the ureter.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the vagina. Representative examples include carcinomas and sarcomas.
A malignant neoplasm involving the trachea
An acute or chronic inflammatory disease affecting the esophageal wall.
Inflammation of the vagina due to thinning of the vaginal wall and decreased lubrication associated with reduced estrogen levels at menopause.
A rare autosomal dominant inherited disorder characterized by the presence of small areas of increased density throughout the bones.
A rare lymphoma that arises from the trachea. Signs and symptoms include dyspnea, cough, wheezing, and stridor.
A rare malignant soft tissue neoplasm that arises from the trachea.

Benign and malignant neoplasms which arise from or metastasize to the trigeminal or fifth cranial nerve which provides sensory innervation to the face, oral cavity and sinuses and the muscles of mastication. Clinical features may include facial pain or sensory loss or weakness of jaw closure.
A neoplasm involving a frontal lobe.

An endocrine disorder characterized by excessive production of aldosterone by the adrenal glands. Causes include adrenal gland adenoma and adrenal gland hyperplasia. The overproduction of aldosterone results in sodium and water retention and hypokalemia. Patients present with high blood pressure, muscle weakness, and headache.
Arthropathy that is not permanent.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the vagina. Representative examples include vaginal infection, vaginal polyp, and vaginal squamous cell carcinoma.
Accumulation of iron in internal organs.

A rare lung disorder characterized by the filling of the pulmonary alveoli with proteinaceous material which stains positive with periodic acid-Schiff stain. It may be idiopathic or secondary due to hematologic malignancies or the inhalation of mineral dusts. Signs and symptoms include dyspnea, cough and low grade fever.

A parasitic infection caused by Trypanosoma cruzi. It is transmitted by insect bites. It is characterized by an acute and chronic phase; in the acute phase patients may have fever, malaise, and swelling at the site of the insect bite. In the chronic phase patients develop hepatosplenomegaly, lymphadenopathy, cardiomyopathy and arrhythmias.
A peripheral nerve lesion that involves the ulnar nerve.

Disease involving the radial nerve. Clinical features include weakness of elbow extension, elbow flexion, supination of the forearm, wrist and finger extension, and thumb abduction. Sensation may be impaired over regions of the dorsal forearm. Common sites of compression or traumatic injury include the axilla and radial groove of the humerus.
A malignant neoplasm involving the sigmoid colon.
Chronic form of salpingo-oophoritis.
A decrease in the number of neutrophils found in the blood.
An abnormality in which a part of a structure in one or both eyes is missing.
A cancer that involves the intrahepatic bile duct.
Heart disease which occurs as a result of a primary pulmonary disease. Cor pulmonale most often manifests as right ventricular hypertrophy; it can also lead to right ventricular failure.

A condition characterized by the dilated tortuous veins of the spermatic cord with a marked left-sided predominance. Adverse effect on male fertility occurs when varicocele leads to an increased scrotal (and testicular) temperature and reduced testicular volume.
A lymphoma that involves the retroperitoneal space.
A sarcoma involving a retroperitoneal space.
A carcinoma that arises from epithelial cells of the retroperitoneal space.
An labyrinthitis caused by infection with Viruses.
The turning inward (inversion) of the edge of the eyelid, with the tarsal cartilage turned inward toward the eyeball. (Dorland, 27th ed)
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the vulva.
A benign smooth muscle neoplasm arising from the vagina. It is characterized by the presence of spindle cells with cigar-shaped nuclei, interlacing fascicles, and a whorled pattern.
A ischemic disease that involves the retina.
A usually small tearing of the retina occurring when the vitreous separates from the retina. It may lead to retinal detachment. Symptoms include flashes and floaters.
A peripheral nerve lesion that involves the sciatic nerve.
Acute kidney injury associated with microangiopathic hemolytic anemia and thrombocytopenia.
Secondary glaucoma caused by either excessive size or spheric shape of the lens.
A bursitis that involves the olecranon.
A disease involving the vestibulocochlear nerve.
